popupInfo.title:
The Chicago region has combined sewers, which means sanitary sewage and stormwater runoff are collected in a single pipe system. Under dry weather, or normal rain events, the system is able to process both types of water. However, during more substantial rains, the system can’t process the water rapidly enough, resulting in combined sewer overflows (CSOs), by which diluted sewage
is released into the Chicago River, Lake Michigan, or peoples’ basements. CSOs are a serious threat to water quality. In 2009, there were 261 outfall locations in the CAWS; 2,036 discharge events occurred, resulting in flooded basements, closed beaches, and threats to drinking water quality.
